climbs.name: Who Cut The Cheese?
climbs.fa: Alan Bartlett and Mike Wilson, March, 1994

content.description: Same start as "Hot Dog in a Bun". Move left on a ramp to a groove/fist crack.
content.location: Just left of "Hot Dog in a Bun".

content.description: Climbs a left-leaning dogleg crack past a bush. Gear belay and easy walk-off to climber's right.
content.location:
About 150 feet right of

Lee's Health Studio (aka The Dehab Clinic)

climbs.name: Lee's Health Studio (aka The Dehab Clinic)

content.description:
This route lies on the southern part of the West Tiers, about 90 yards right of

Blood and Cuts

(5.10a). It ascends a very prominent left diagonalling dike (3 bolts), then up into a crack. It is easily visible from the road. One of the better routes in the vicinity and well worth doing.

climbs.name: Hot Dog in a Bun
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Cyndie Bransford, Steve McCallister & Rick Corbin, February 1991

content.description:
This fun route is located about 125 feet left of

Blood And Cuts

, and 70 feet right of the descent gully. It climbs an unusual groove/chute which ends just below the top of the lower tier. Lots of stems, chimney, and other moves, that make you feel like, well...a hot dog in a bun. The crux is the transition from the groove to high angle josh friction. 2 of 5 stars. Walk down the gully.
Blocky pulls on the lower dike lead to hard series of moves to gain the upper right hand fork of the crack.
content.protection: 5 bolts, medium nuts, pieces from a purple Camalot up to gold.
content.location: This worthwhile route lies just right of Lee's Health Studio on a prominent left leaning dike.

content.description: This route, located on the lower tier approximately 125' south of a bolted waterchute (Hot Dog in a Bun), ascends a sustained vertical finger to hand / fist crack. As the route name implies, there are some jagged edges in the crack but the rock quality is good.
content.protection: This climb protects well with small to medium sized cams and medium stoppers. Medium sized cams are needed for an anchor.
